**E. Zero-Shot Parsing: Implementation Details**  
The zero-shot parsing experiments utilized the AllenNLP implementation (Gardner et al., 2018) of the deep biaffine attention model proposed by Dozat and Manning (2017). The primary modification involved substituting the trainable GloVe embeddings with fixed, multilingual BERT embeddings (Devlin et al., 2018). Specifically, the built-in AllenNLP embeddings were employed using default settings without performing any fine-tuning on the BERT model. Furthermore, UD subcategorization of edge labels was excluded from the analysis, as these subtypes are frequently language-specific. A complete list of hyperparameters is provided in Table 6.

Three models were trained for each target language using identical hyperparameters. The English model was trained on the UD v2.5 English-EWT dataset, while models for French, Russian, Chinese, Korean, and Japanese were trained on their respective GSD datasets (v2.5). Standard train/validation/test splits were applied to all corpora. Model evaluation was conducted on the GSD and PUD datasets. The per-label F-scores utilized for linear modeling in this paper represent the average F-scores derived from the three models trained per language.

Although various Neural Machine Translation (NMT) architectures exist, the standard approach employs multi-layer encoders and decoders to execute translation tasks. These architectures typically incorporate residual connections (He et al., 2016) between layers, defined by the equation $H^l = \text{LAYER}(H^{l-1}; \Theta^l) + H^{l-1}$, where $H^l$ represents the output of the $l$-th layer, $\text{LAYER}(\cdot)$ denotes the layer function, and $\Theta^l$ signifies the layer parameters.

In this study, the state-of-the-art Transformer model serves as the baseline. Specifically, the encoder comprises a stack of $L$ identical layers, each containing two primary subcomponents: a self-attention mechanism followed by a feedforward network. Layer normalization (Ba et al., 2016) is applied to the input of each subcomponent (a configuration known as pre-norm), and residual skip connections (He et al., 2016) are utilized to add the input of each subcomponent to its corresponding output. Formally, this process is expressed as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
O_e^l &= \text{ATTN}(Q_e^l, K_e^l, V_e^l; \Theta_e^l) + H_e^{l-1}, \\
H_e^l &= \text{FFN}(\text{LN}(O_e^l); \Theta_e^l) + O_e^l,
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
$$

where $\text{LN}(\cdot)$, $\text{ATTN}(\cdot)$, and $\text{FFN}(\cdot)$ represent layer normalization, the attention mechanism, and the feedforward network (incorporating ReLU activation), respectively. The query, key, and value vectors $\{Q_e^l, K_e^l, V_e^l\}$ are derived from the normalized output of the preceding $(l-1)$-th encoder layer, $\text{LN}(H_e^{l-1})$.
